{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492671"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:40:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:40:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1127"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1127"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.16,0.03,0.05,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1127"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69136"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1127"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1127"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54593"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3374"},{"type":"tags","id":"3455"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49627"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69136"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents with a three month history of increasing dysphagia and weight loss. He now struggles to keep liquids down. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and is unable to walk more than half a flight of stairs without becoming breathless.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is a palpable mass in his left supraclavicular fossa. A stenosing adenocarcinoma is found in the lower oesophagus. The endoscope can only just be passed through the tumour. This lesion is 10 cm long, as judged on CT staging, and the presence of enlarged supraclavicular lymph nodes is confirmed. The patient lives six hour\u0027s drive from the treating hospital.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stent insertion","Feeding jejunostomy","Radiotherapy","Definitive chemoradiotherapy","Neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy follow by oesophagectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhatever form of treatment is to be given, it will be palliative. He has stage IV disease and his prognosis is limited. His current problem is his inability to swallow anything of sustenance. Whilst radiotherapy is often advantageous in such circumstances, this is a large tumour and he would require wide field treatment and some form of feeding supplementation during treatment. In addition he lives a long way from the treatment centre and a course of radiotherapy is likely to be very inconvenient. A \u003Cstrong\u003Estent\u003C/strong\u003E will probably offer him the most effective relief of his symptoms. It must be remembered that stents have their own complications. About 60% of patients with stents will experience minor adverse events including chest pain, gastro-oesophageal reflux, stent migration and tumour overgrowth of the stent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst a feeding jejunostomy could be used in conjunction with a course of palliative radiotherapy, there is little to commend feeding alone if no attempt is going to be made to improve the patient\u0027s swallowing. Radiotherapy is a well-accepted treatment modality for patients with advanced disease - however, the dysphagia will get worse before its gets better and patients such as this one will require some form of supplemental feeding during and for a few weeks after treatment. These supplements can be given via a nasoenteric feeding tube or a gastrostomy. Treatment options will vary, depending on the patient\u0027s circumstances - this patient lives a considerable distance from the treating hospital and insertion of a stent is likely to be most expedient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A mesh stent provides effective symptomatic relief in patients with incurable oesophageal cancer and incapacitating dysphagia."],"references":["Shah, MA, Kennedy, EB, Catenacci, DV, et al. \u0027Treatment of Locally Advanced Esophageal Carcinoma: ASCO Guideline\u0027, Journal of Clinical Oncology. 2020;38(23):2677-2694. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32568633/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54593"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1127"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54593"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T11:03:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T21:10:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1127"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69136"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","syn